        }
    ),
    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='# Useful Life of Starlink Satellites and Replacement Frequency\n\n## Estimated Useful Lives\n\nBased on the Significant Accounting Policies note, SpaceX estimates the following useful lives for its satellite assets:\n\n| Satellite Type | Estimated Useful Life |\n|---|---|\n| **Broadband satellites** | **5 years** |\n| **First-generation mobile satellites** | **3 years** |\n| **Satellites (general range disclosed)** | **3–5 years** |\n\n## Criteria for Useful Life Estimation\n\nThe Company estimates the useful lives of its satellite assets based on the following factors:\n\n- **Engineering studies**\n- **Historical on-orbit performance**\n- **Propellant life**\n- **Utilization patterns**\n- **Design enhancements across generations**\n- **Planned transitions to newer satellite technology**\n\nAdditionally, for satellite assets specifically, the Company considers factors such as **on-orbit performance, orbit-raise timing, expected service capability, and the evolution of constellation density and technology**.\n\n## Early Deorbiting and Replacement\n\nThe Company discloses that it **often deorbits satellites before the end of their useful lives**, primarily to reduce degradation risks that could impair its autonomous collision avoidance system and compromise safety. This means actual replacement cycles may be **shorter** than the estimated 3–5 year useful lives.\n\nThe Risk Factors note reinforces this, stating:\n\n> "The useful life of our satellites is inherently shorter than that of the information technology systems and infrastructure they host. As a result, we must periodically launch replacement satellites as existing satellites reach the end of their useful lives and are decommissioned."\n\n## Capitalization and Refurbishment Policies\n\n- **Maintenance and repairs** that do not extend the lives of assets are **expensed as incurred**.\n- **Significant refurbishment, renewals, and enhancements** that increase functionality, output, or expected life are **capitalized and depreciated ratably** over the identified useful life.\n- Satellites include costs to build (parts, labor, allocated overhead) as well as **capitalized launch costs** incurred by the Space segment.\n- The Company also **capitalizes certain interest costs** associated with significant construction of property, plant, and equipment, including satellites.\n\n## Revision of Estimates\n\nManagement periodically reviews useful life estimates with engineering and operations teams and revises them as additional data becomes available. When useful lives are determined to be shorter or longer than originally estimated, the Company **adjusts the rate of depreciation** to reflect the revised useful lives.\n\n## Materiality of Estimate Changes\n\nThe Company disclosed that if the average useful life of its satellite assets had been changed by **one year**, it would have had an approximately **$480 million** impact on operating income for the year ended December 31, 2025, and approximately **$170 million** for the three months ended March 31, 2026—underscoring the financial significance of these estimates.\n\n## Summary\n\nStarlink broadband satellites are estimated to have a **5-year useful life**, while first-generation mobile satellites have a **3-year useful life**. However, satellites are frequently **deorbited before reaching the end of their estimated useful lives** for safety reasons, meaning the effective replacement cycle can be shorter. The Company must therefore **periodically launch replacement satellites** to maintain constellation capacity, with replacement driven by both end-of-life decommissioning and proactive early deorbiting protocols.',
