    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided document chunks, here is a summary of SpaceX\'s disclosures regarding capital expenditures for satellites, satellite production costs, launch costs, and the ongoing investment required to maintain the Starlink constellation:\n\n**Capital Expenditures and Ongoing Investment**\nSpaceX notes that it has incurred significant capital expenditures and expects to increase them substantially in the future to design, develop, and deploy its satellite constellations, launch vehicles, ground stations, and manufacturing facilities. These expenditures include R&D, construction, acquisition of property and equipment, and "ongoing maintenance and upgrades to ensure reliability and competitiveness." \n\nThe company explicitly warns that it may choose to accelerate these investments at any time, which could result in periods of reduced profitability as it prioritizes long-term growth over near-term financial performance. This is reflected in the Connectivity segment\'s capital expenditures, which increased $680 million to $4.18 billion in 2025, and increased another $518 million to $1.33 billion in Q1 2026. These increases were primarily driven by higher satellite and ground equipment costs as the company continues to increase its number of satellites and grow the network.\n\n**Satellite Manufacturing and Production Costs**\nSpaceX highlights its vertically integrated satellite platform as a key competitive advantage. Unlike traditional manufacturers that rely on fragmented supply chains, SpaceX controls satellite design, architecture, chip design, software, power systems, final assembly, and launch operations in-house. This high-throughput manufacturing capability enables the company to rapidly iterate on next-generation satellites and produce them at scale—thousands per year—which accelerates deployment timelines and allows for capital efficiency that is difficult for competitors to replicate. \n\nThe company expects that as it scales, Connectivity cost of revenue will decrease as a percentage of revenue as it drives efficiencies in its next-generation satellites, Starlink Kits, and ground infrastructure. However, R&D expenses will continue to increase in absolute dollars to fund the development, build, and testing of next-generation satellites.\n\n**Launch Costs**\nThe cost of satellites includes the costs to build them (parts, labor, allocated overhead) as well as capitalized launch costs incurred by the Space segment to launch them into orbit (which includes an allocation of flight vehicle costs). \n\nFor Starlink satellite launches, the company does not recognize inter-segment revenue. Instead, those launch costs are capitalized into "satellites" within Property, plant, and equipment, net. Because SpaceX allocates a significant amount of its launch capacity to the Connectivity segment, the relative increase in Starlink satellite launches (from 89 in 2024 to 122 in 2025) results in relatively more launch operations and overhead costs being capitalized into the Connectivity segment. \n\n**Recurring Nature of Satellite Investment**\nThe investment in the Starlink constellation is highly recurring. As the number of satellites placed into orbit grows, the Connectivity segment experiences continuous increases in depreciation from these capitalized launch and satellite costs, which directly drives up the segment\'s cost of revenue. For example, in Q1 2026, Connectivity cost of revenue increased by $437 million, primarily due to $276 million in higher depreciation from capitalized launch and satellite costs. This reflects the ongoing cycle of manufacturing, launching, and depreciating assets required to scale and maintain the constellation.',
        error=None,
        metadata=None,
        done=False,
        success=True
    ),
