2026-06-24 17:12:59,622 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## FY2025 Connectivity Segment: EBITDA-to-Operating-Income Gap\n\n### Reported Figures (Year Ended December 31, 2025)\n\n| Metric (Connectivity Segment) | FY2025 ($ millions) |\n|---|---|\n| Income from operations (GAAP) | $4,423 |\n| Add: Depreciation and amortization | $2,376 |\n| Add: Share-based compensation | $369 |\n| Add: Restructuring charges | $0 |\n| Add: Impairment | $0 |\n| **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** | **$7,168** |\n\n### Implied EBITDA-to-Operating-Income Gap\n\n**Gap = $7,168M − $4,423M = $2,745 million**\n\nThis gap equals the sum of the two add-backs ($2,376M D&A + $369M SBC = $2,745M), confirming the reconciliation. In proportional terms:\n\n- The gap is **~62.06% of operating income** ($2,745M / $4,423M).\n- **Depreciation and amortization alone accounts for ~86.56% of the gap** ($2,376M / $2,745M), with share-based compensation making up the remainder.\n\nSo while Adjusted EBITDA presents the Connectivity segment as generating $7.2B of "cash-like" operating profit, $2.4B of that uplift is depreciation — and the bulk of that depreciation is satellite-related.\n\n---\n\n### Why Satellite Depreciation Is Economically Recurring (Despite Being Excluded from Adjusted EBITDA)\n\nThe S-1 defines Adjusted EBITDA as net income excluding (among other items) "depreciation and amortization," and management\'s stated rationale is that D&A "do[es] not directly reflect our ongoing operating performance." Satellite depreciation is swept into this exclusion as part of the broader D&A line. However, the same filing\'s disclosures make clear that, for SpaceX\'s satellite constellation, this exclusion is economically misleading for several reasons:\n\n**1. Satellites have very short useful lives — 3 to 5 years.**\nPer the Significant Accounting Policies note:\n- Broadband (Starlink) satellites: **5-year useful life**\n- First-generation mobile satellites: **3-year useful life**\n\nThese lives are far shorter than typical PP&E (buildings, terrestrial infrastructure), so the depreciation is being recognized over a horizon that closely matches the actual consumption of the asset.\n\n**2. Satellites are frequently deorbited *before* end of useful life.**\nThe filing discloses that SpaceX "often deorbits satellites before the end of their useful lives" to reduce degradation risks to its autonomous collision-avoidance system. The Risk Factors reinforce this: *"The useful life of our satellites is inherently shorter than that of the information technology systems and infrastructure they host. As a result, we must periodically launch replacement satellites as existing satellites reach the end of their useful lives and are decommissioned."* The effective replacement cycle is therefore shorter than even the 3–5 year book life.\n\n**3. Replacement is mandatory to maintain service — it is not optional capex.**\nTo preserve constellation capacity and coverage, SpaceX must continuously manufacture, launch, and deploy replacement satellites. This is a structural, non-discretionary cost of remaining in the connectivity business. The Risk Factors and MD&A describe ongoing capital expenditures to "design, develop, and deploy" the constellation and "ongoing maintenance and upgrades to ensure reliability."\n\n**4. The cash outflow is already visible in Connectivity capex.**\nConnectivity segment capital expenditures rose **$680 million to $4.18 billion in 2025**, "primarily driven by higher satellite and ground equipment costs as the company continues to increase its number of satellites and grow the network." Capex rose another $518 million to $1.33 billion in Q1 2026. The depreciation being added back in Adjusted EBITDA is the GAAP amortization of these very same cash outflows — i.e., the cash has already been (or is being) spent.\n\n**5. The depreciation is actively flowing through cost of revenue.**\nThe filing explicitly notes that as the in-orbit fleet grows, "the Connectivity segment experiences continuous increases in depreciation from these capitalized launch and satellite costs, which directly drives up the segment\'s cost of revenue." In Q1 2026 alone, Connectivity cost of revenue rose $437 million, of which **$276 million was higher depreciation from capitalized launch and satellite costs** — confirming that satellite depreciation is a recurring, growing operating cost, not a one-time or non-cash-only item.\n\n**6. The estimate is highly material and sensitive.**\nSpaceX discloses that a one-year change in the average useful-life estimate for satellite assets would have impacted FY2025 operating income by approximately **$480 million** (and ~$170 million for Q1 2026). This sensitivity underscores that satellite depreciation is a large, recurring charge that materially shapes reported profitability.\n\n### Economic Conclusion\n\nFor most businesses, excluding D&A from EBITDA is defensible because the underlying assets are long-lived and replacement is lumpy/optional. For SpaceX\'s Connectivity segment, the opposite is true: satellites are short-lived (3–5 years), frequently deorbited early, and must be replaced on a near-continuous basis to keep the constellation operational. The depreciation add-back therefore converts a structurally recurring economic cost — the periodic replacement of the in-orbit fleet — into a "non-cash" exclusion, even though the corresponding cash is being spent in real time (evidenced by $4.18B of Connectivity capex in 2025). In substance, satellite depreciation functions much like a recurring lease or capacity-maintenance payment: it is the GAAP recognition of an unavoidable, repeating economic outflow required to sustain the business. Excluding it from Adjusted EBITDA overstates the segment\'s sustainable cash-generating power by roughly $2.4 billion in FY2025.\n\n---\n\n### Sources\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Segment reporting / Connectivity reconciliation, Significant Accounting Policies (satellite useful lives), Risk Factors, and MD&A (capex and cost-of-revenue drivers)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
